      Fake pod shop
   =20
 =20

The fastest-growing and most attractive sort of hedge fund these days=C2=A0=
is the multi-manager =E2=80=9Cpod shop.=E2=80=9D These funds=C2=A0hire=C2=
=A0lots of different portfolio managers running uncorrelated strategies; th=
ey monitor the managers closely, minimize directional market exposure,=C2=
=A0allocate capital based on performance, and take=C2=A0capital away rapidl=
y from managers who have=C2=A0losses. The resulting fund is exactly what bi=
g allocators want: The fund offers a steady stream of returns that are not =
correlated to the market, it has very low risk, and it is a big stable inst=
itution that can manage their money forever.=C2=A0
This is such a good model that people keep trying to get into it; we talked=
 on Monday=C2=A0about Bank of New York Mellon=E2=80=99s plans to get into t=
he pod-shop business. (They plan to distinguish themselves from the leading=
 players by charging lower fees and being nicer to their PMs.)
But it is also such a good model that people are apparently tempted to=C2=
=A0fake=C2=A0it. Like, write a business plan hitting the traditional beats =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe allocate our capital among a bunch of diverse un=
correlated portfolio managers,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cwe manage risk by pulling=
=C2=A0capital from PMs who have a big drawdown,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cwe make m=
oney consistently in all markets,=E2=80=9D etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and go out a=
nd raise money and then give it all to one guy to bet on Bitcoin or whateve=
r. This does not strike me as a good plan, but here is a US Securities and =
Exchange Commission enforcement action from last week:

The Securities and Exchange Commission [Thursday]=C2=A0charged John Hughes,=
 president and chief compliance officer of registered investment adviser Pr=
ophecy Asset Management LP, for his involvement in a multi-year fraud that =
concealed losses of hundreds of millions of dollars from investors. ...
According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, Hughes led investors to believe t=
hat their investments were protected from loss, telling them the funds=E2=
=80=99 capital was shared among dozens of sub-advisers who traded in liquid=
 securities and posted cash collateral to offset any trading losses they in=
curred. In reality, most of the funds=E2=80=99 capital went to one sub-advi=
ser, who incurred massive trading losses that far exceeded the cash collate=
ral he had contributed. In addition, Hughes caused the funds to invest in h=
ighly illiquid investments, which also resulted in substantial losses to th=
e funds. Hughes concealed these losses by fabricating documents and engagin=
g in a series of sham transactions to cover-up the true financial condition=
 of the funds. The complaint also alleges that Hughes deceived investors ab=
out the diversification and trading strategies in two other funds. By 2020,=
 after losses in funds that Prophecy Asset Management managed amounted to m=
ore than $350 million, Hughes and Prophecy Asset Management indefinitely su=
spended redemptions by investors.

There is also a  federal criminal case; Hughes pleaded guilty to a securiti=
es fraud conspiracy =E2=80=9Cthat wiped out Prophecy=E2=80=99s funds and ca=
used over $294 million in losses to the victims.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Prophecy not exactly a traditional pod shop: The sub-advisers were not empl=
oyees, and the protection against drawdowns was not just =E2=80=9Cwe take a=
way capital from people who lose money=E2=80=9D but also =E2=80=9Cthe sub-a=
dvisers have to post cash collateral of 10% of their allocation, so that if=
 they lose any money they can pay us back.=E2=80=9D But it touches on many =
of=C2=A0the same=C2=A0ideas:

Under the Prophecy model, while sub-advisers were permitted a percentage of=
 profits, they also were also responsible for covering losses up to an agre=
ed amount. Typically, PAM required sub-advisers to post 10% of the agreed u=
pon trading allocation as cash collateral to be available to cover possible=
 losses. ...
The premise of steady, single-digit returns protected against loss was base=
d on misrepresentations of active risk management where sub-advisers were p=
urportedly routinely monitored with respect to diversification, cash collat=
eral, and liquidity of trading strategies. =E2=80=A6
Hughes and Individual 1, through PAM, represented that Prophecy=E2=80=99s c=
apital was allocated to dozens of sub-advisers employing multiple diverse a=
nd even =E2=80=9Cunique=E2=80=9D trading strategies. For example, PAM distr=
ibuted monthly =E2=80=9Cfact sheets=E2=80=9D to investors stating that Prop=
hecy =E2=80=9Cseeks to generate returns by making notional allocations to a=
 diverse group of subadvisers running a variety of discretionary, systemati=
c and unique investment strategies.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
Hughes and Individual 1, through PAM, distributed offering and marketing do=
cuments that also stated that Prophecy protected its capital from losses by=
 holding cash collateral contributed by each sub-adviser. PAM represented t=
hat if a sub-adviser=E2=80=99s losses absorbed 50% or more of its cash coll=
ateral deposit, PAM would stop the sub-adviser=E2=80=99s trading and requir=
e additional collateral or a reduction in exposure.

It=E2=80=99s just that that wasn=E2=80=99t true. Prophecy allegedly allocat=
ed most of its capital to one manager, called =E2=80=9CIndividual 2=E2=80=
=9D in the SEC complaint and =E2=80=9CCo-conspirator-2=E2=80=9D in the crim=
inal one, and covered that up in its investor reports=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cby pres=
enting his total allocation as if Individual 2 were multiple, individualize=
d sub-advisers.=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9CSince in or around 2019, Co-conspirator-=
2 was also the CEO and President of a multi-billion dollar company that own=
ed and managed large and diversified retail franchises,=E2=80=9D  says the =
criminal case;   Bloomberg reports that it=E2=80=99s Brian Kahn, the=C2=A0c=
hief executive officer of Franchise Group Inc., which owns Vitamin=C2=A0Sho=
ppe.)=C2=A0And Prophecy=C2=A0did not actually have the 10% cash collateral,=
 or even stop the guy out when he had big losses:

As of January 2019, Prophecy=E2=80=99s total cash deposit balance equaled a=
 mere 0.77% of the reported gross market value of its assets. By July 2019,=
 Prophecy=E2=80=99s cash deposit balance dipped even lower, to 0.05%.
Prophecy had all but abandoned its cash deposit requirement for Individual =
2, notwithstanding Individual 2=E2=80=99s outsized allotment of Prophecy=E2=
=80=99s trading capital and enormous trading losses.
For instance, Individual 2=E2=80=99s trading losses exceeded the amount of =
the cash collateral Individual 2 had contributed by: $55 million in 2018; $=
216 million in 2019; and $328 million in 2020. ...
From January 2018 through March 2020, Individual 2=E2=80=99s trading losses=
 exceeded the balance of his cash collateral for all but one month.=C2=A0

If you lose money every month for two years you will probably lose your job=
 at a traditional multi-manager fund. But not at a fake one!

 =20
   =20
      Silly pod shops
   =20
 =20

Elsewhere in =E2=80=9Cmulti-manager funds are a good business=E2=80=9D:

The rise of multi-manager hedge funds has led to a =E2=80=9Cmerry-go-round=
=E2=80=9D of portfolio managers being offered =E2=80=9Csilly=E2=80=9D amoun=
ts of money, according to the co-founder of Europe=E2=80=99s largest hedge =
fund.
Sir Paul Marshall, co-founder of Marshall Wace, told an investment conferen=
ce in Hong Kong on Wednesday the dominance of multi-manager platforms had r=
eshaped the industry because they were =E2=80=9Cpaying incredible amounts o=
f money to target people=E2=80=9D.
=E2=80=9CEverybody wants that Cristiano Ronaldo on their team, but there ar=
en=E2=80=99t very many Cristiano Ronaldos,=E2=80=9D said Marshall, who co-f=
ounded the London-based group in 1997 with Ian Wace. =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99=
s happening is everybody=E2=80=99s getting paid the same as Cristiano Ronal=
do.=E2=80=9D

The particular form of good business here is that the pass-through fee mode=
l at these funds allows them to bill their compensation expense directly to=
 their clients:

Under this model, the manager passes on all costs =E2=80=94 including offic=
e rents, technology and data, salaries, bonuses and even client entertainme=
nt =E2=80=94 to their end investors. The idea is that managers invest heavi=
ly in areas such as talent and technology, with the cost more than offset b=
y resulting performance. They then tend to charge a 20-30 per cent performa=
nce fee on top.
The pass-through model fuels practices such as sign-on bonuses running into=
 millions or tens of millions of dollars, paid sabbaticals and payouts to i=
ndividual portfolio managers that can be 20 to 30 per cent of profits, all =
of which are designed to lure and retain the top performers.

This creates upward pressure on hedge fund pay: If your pay is=C2=A0set=C2=
=A0by your boss, but=C2=A0paid=C2=A0by your clients, there is not a ton of =
constraint on how high it can=C2=A0be. It=E2=80=99s not your boss=E2=80=99s=
 money. =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s pay you $100 million, bill the clients, and =
see if they complain,=E2=80=9D your boss can say; there is=C2=A0some=C2=A0l=
evel at which they will complain, but apparently nobody has found it yet. G=
reat business.
Marshall is responding to this pay pressure not only by complaining at conf=
erences but also by passing through some of his compensation expenses:
The competition for talent has forced traditional hedge fund players such a=
s Marshall=E2=80=99s firm to adapt. Its flagship Eureka hedge fund this yea=
r added a =E2=80=9Ccompensation surcharge=E2=80=9D worth as much as 0.75 pe=
r cent of the fund=E2=80=99s value, to be used to reward high performers, a=
 decision Marshall said at the time was taken because =E2=80=9Cmulti-manage=
r platforms are driving a bidding war for talent=E2=80=9D.
It=E2=80=99s like when the Affordable Care Act passed and some restaurants =
 added a stunt surcharge to customer bills to pay for health insurance; the=
 message was=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cour employee costs have gone up, so we will pass=
 them on to you in a surly showy way.=E2=80=9D Only here the cost is not he=
alth insurance but competition from Citadel.

 =20
   =20
      Bridgewater
   =20
 =20

We   talked yesterday about Rob Copeland=E2=80=99s new book,=C2=A0The Fund,=
 about Bridgewater Associates, the world=E2=80=99s largest hedge fund, and =
its founder Ray Dalio. In particular, I mentioned two things:
=09A story Copeland tells about some underlings commissioning a report to D=
alio about his own=C2=A0investment ideas,=C2=A0which apparently did not per=
form=C2=A0that well.=09My   half-joking model of Bridgewater as a systemati=
c investment firm, in which a computer does the investing and keeps the hum=
an employees from interfering by giving them baroque tasks like ranking eac=
h others=E2=80=99 believability. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s very important that =
you rate all of your colleagues on 38 factors after each meeting,=E2=80=9D =
the computer snickers, and the humans are distracted by that while it gets =
on with the investing.

A reader who used to work at Bridgewater emailed=C2=A0that these points are=
 more related than I thought:

You wrote=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cthe computer's main problem is keeping the 1,5=
00 human employees busy so that they don=E2=80=99t interfere with its perfe=
ct rationality.=E2=80=9D You missed that the story right above that comment=
 =E2=80=93 confronting Ray about his trading performance =E2=80=93 was a ra=
ther elegant attempt at doing just that. ...
Of course Bridgewater is systematic =E2=80=93 not =E2=80=9Cquant=E2=80=9D i=
n the Rennaissance=C2=A0Technologies sense, but systematic in the sense of =
=E2=80=9Ctrades are determined by computers running complicated calculation=
s across a thousand different rulesets.=E2=80=9D
95% of the trades are made by the system. But also of course Ray could do w=
hatever he wanted to, he owned the place (at the time). The analysis Copela=
nd heard about had nothing to do with Ray=E2=80=99s pure ability as a trade=
r =E2=80=93 they were looking at the times that Ray overruled the computer.=
=C2=A0The point wasn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9CRay is a bad investor,=E2=80=9D it =
was =E2=80=9CRay shouldn=E2=80=99t overrule the computer.=E2=80=9D

The computer called Dalio=E2=80=99s underlings into its little computer off=
ice and was like =E2=80=9Coh boy do I have a task for you, you have to tell=
 that Dalio guy to stop messing with my trades.=E2=80=9D And they were like=
 =E2=80=9Cthank you, computer,=C2=A0this is an incredible opportunity for r=
adical transparency and ideas meritocracy,=E2=80=9D I guess.

 =20
   =20
      AT1s
   =20
 =20

When UBS Group AG acquired Credit Suisse Group AG in March, Credit Suisse=
=E2=80=99s additional tier 1 capital securities were   written down to zero=
. Holders of the AT1s lost all their money, but more importantly they were=
=C2=A0offended. Those AT1s were not=C2=A0supposed=C2=A0to be written down t=
o zero, they argued: While their terms said they would go to zero in certai=
n sorts of crisis at Credit Suisse, what actually happened was not the exac=
t sort of crisis that was supposed to trigger them. Also Credit Suisse=E2=
=80=99s common shareholders got paid (a little) in the deal, and the AT1s w=
ere supposed to be senior to the common, so what the heck?
I think it is fair to say that this is the most offensive thing that has ev=
er happened to investors in the AT1 market, and those investors swore etern=
al vendetta on UBS and Credit Suisse and Switzerland generally, and I was l=
ike =E2=80=9Clol nobody on earth has a shorter memory than the market for w=
eird bank credit instruments,=E2=80=9D and   here=E2=80=99s Bloomberg News =
today:

UBS Group AG=E2=80=99s hotly-anticipated sale of additional tier 1 bonds, i=
ts first since Credit Suisse roiled the market with a historic writedown, h=
as pulled in roughly 10 times the bids for the debt on offer.
The Swiss bank is selling two dollar-denominated bonds on Wednesday for $3.=
5 billion in total, with combined orders of more than $36 billion. =E2=80=
=A6
The stampede to get into the deal marks a complete reversal from March, whe=
n roughly $17 billion Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s were wiped out as part o=
f a UBS takeover brokered by the Swiss government. That triggered the bigge=
st daily loss in the market=E2=80=99s history, and sent yields soaring abov=
e 15% for the first time, according to a Bloomberg index. UBS=E2=80=99s off=
ering solidifies the recovery of the asset class, which has seen yields dro=
p by nearly 500 basis points from their peak in March.

Good for them. To be fair, the new AT1s convert into common equity when the=
y are triggered, rather than being written down to zero, which avoids the p=
otential unfairness of what happened to the Credit Suisse ones:
Laurent Frings, head of credit research at Aegon Asset Management, said the=
 equity conversion mechanism =E2=80=94 a likely response to the Credit Suis=
se drama =E2=80=94 was also positive. =E2=80=9CIn terms of optics and the l=
ikelihood of seeing another trigger happening and shareholders getting some=
thing versus AT1 holders getting zero, this is definitely better.=E2=80=9D
So, yes, the market does remember March.

 =20
   =20
      NFT=C2=A0Stuff / AI Stuff
   =20
 =20

Sure!
One of OpenSea=E2=80=99s biggest investors has marked down by 90% its stake=
 in the struggling non-fungible-token marketplace, implying that the former=
 crypto darling is now valued at $1.4 billion or less on paper. Coatue Mana=
gement, a New York=E2=80=93based hedge and venture fund, slashed the value =
of its $120 million stake in the company to $13 million as of the second qu=
arter of this year, according to a document viewed by The Information.
Only $1.4 billion for the leading NFT marketplace, in 2023, how about that.=
=C2=A0Elsewhere:

In 2021, at the height of the investor frenzy for crypto startups, entrepre=
neur Chris Horne raised $2 million in seed funding for Filta, a marketplace=
 on which customers could buy and sell custom nonfungible token face filter=
s that could digitally augment their face, say, by adding cat whiskers or a=
 block head. But by the time the company launched in late summer of 2022, e=
nthusiasm for crypto had waned and Filta was faltering.=C2=A0
So Horne pivoted to the new hottest sector: artificial intelligence. He dit=
ched the NFT idea, and this year relaunched Filta as a generative AI-powere=
d digital pet, one that talks and can offer its owner emotional support. Th=
e technology behind his new company is OpenAI=E2=80=99s large language mode=
l, ChatGPT. And Horne is running his new Filta venture off the capital he r=
aised for his original concept.

That is probably the most cynical version of =E2=80=9Ccrypto guy=C2=A0pivot=
s to AI=E2=80=9D I have ever read, but even here=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s an obvio=
us improvement. Before, he was going to sell people pictures of cats on the=
 blockchain. Now, he is going to sell people pictures of cats that will tal=
k and offer emotional support and not=C2=A0be on the blockchain. Strictly b=
etter!
Oh and elsewhere in =E2=80=9Ccrypto guy=C2=A0pivots to AI=E2=80=9D:

Andreessen Horowitz is warning that billions of dollars in AI investments c=
ould be worth a lot less if companies developing the technology are forced =
to pay for the copyrighted data that makes it work.
The VC firm said AI investments are so huge that any new rules around the c=
ontent used to train models "will significantly disrupt" the investment com=
munity's plans and expectations around the technology, according to comment=
s submitted to the US Copyright Office.
"The bottom line is this," the firm, known as a16z, wrote. "Imposing the co=
st of actual or potential copyright liability on the creators of AI models =
will either kill or significantly hamper their development."

If I were a science fiction writer I would be working on a story about=C2=
=A0venture capitalists=C2=A0building a runaway artificial intelligence that=
 will likely enslave or destroy humankind, only to be=C2=A0thwarted by a mi=
nor poet suing them for copyright violations for scraping her poems. Termin=
ator: Fair Use Doctrine.=C2=A0What if fastidious enforcement of intellectua=
l property rights is all that stands between us and annihilation by robots?
More generally, you could have a regulatory model that is like:
=09Nobody will ever again write=C2=A0thoughtful or productive regulations f=
or anything.=09Occasionally the unintended consequences of other, older reg=
ulations will accidentally stop the worst features of some new, impossible-=
to-regulate-thoughtfully thing.

Is US crypto regulation like that? Yes? Is AI-regulation-by-copyright like =
that? No, I am just being silly, but what if it was?

