<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Fresh coffee</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way I like to think about <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33301955.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjEvanBtb3JnYW4taGFkLXNvb=
WUtZmFrZS1uaWNrZWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFp=
bCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25=
leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9af37138" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">commodities futures</a=
> is that there are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/33301955.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
TQtMDktMDMvdGhlLWdvbGRtYW4tc2FjaHMtYWx1bWludW0tY29uc3BpcmFjeS1sYXdzdWl0LWlz=
LW92ZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB496c285b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  two metaphysically distinct=C2=
=A0types of each commodity</a>. Consider nickel. There is the sort of nicke=
l that is produced by producers and delivered to industrial users for makin=
g cars or whatever. If you want nickel to make cars, you will negotiate wit=
h a=C2=A0supplier for a particular amount of a particular grade of nickel t=
o show up in particular shapes at a particular time and location.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then there is the sort of=C2=A0nickel that=
 underlies nickel=C2=A0<em>futures contracts</em>, which is an abstract gen=
eralized kind of nickel used for financial purposes. If you buy a nickel=C2=
=A0futures contract to hedge the price of nickel, you do not intend to turn=
 the futures contract into cars. Ordinarily you will cash out of the future=
s contract at expiration. But in order for the futures contract to hedge th=
e price of nickel, it does need to be=C2=A0<em>possible=C2=A0</em>to turn t=
he contract into actual nickel.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The normal mechanism for this is that the futures exchange has so=
me associated warehouses, and there is nickel in the warehouses, and if you=
 really want to you can turn in a futures contract and get nickel out of th=
e warehouse, or put some nickel=C2=A0in the warehouse and get back a future=
s contract.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s not generally a sensible commercial decision =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0ordinarily you will want to negotiate a particular sort of nickel =
delivered at a particular place =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if prices get too far ou=
t of line you=E2=80=99ll take the warehouse-grade nickel out of the warehou=
se and pay the cost of transporting it to your factory.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that doesn=E2=80=99t happen that often; mo=
stly people are content to leave the nickel in the warehouse and trade cont=
racts referencing it. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/33301955.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjEvanBtb3JnYW4taGFkLXNvbWUtZmFrZS1uaWNrZWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTE=
wODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
C9af37138" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">  talked earlier this year</a> about some nickel that JP=
Morgan Chase &amp; Co. owned in one of these warehouses, which it used for =
years as a substrate for financial contracts. The nickel turned out to be r=
ocks: At some point=C2=A0someone  snuck into the warehouse, stole the nicke=
l and put in bags of rocks instead. It didn=E2=80=99t matter, for years! Th=
e contracts were fine! The nickel played an=C2=A0abstract role; it could si=
t there for years, not being nickel at all, without bothering anyone. And t=
hen one day someone in the warehouse <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/33301955.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjcvdGhlLWNmdGMtY29tZXMtZm9yLWJpbmFuY2U_Y21waWQ=
9QkJEMTEwODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZX=
R0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMTA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB0d0ac5a0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">  kicked it</a>=C2=A0and was like =E2=80=9Cwait =
a minute=E2=80=9D and there was a=C2=A0funny scandal and a rash of confirma=
tory nickel-kicking.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This analysis breaks down, though, for agricul=
tural commodities. You can just plop a few tons of nickel into a warehouse,=
 leave it there forever, and trade futures back and forth referencing that =
nickel. But if you plopped a few tons of<em> pork bellies</em> into a wareh=
ouse and left them there forever, the warehouse would start to smell really=
 bad. Eventually the pork bellies in the warehouse would not be reasonably =
substitutable for the pork bellies available from meat processors, because =
they would have rotted. Perishable=C2=A0commodities cannot remain abstracte=
d in warehouses indefinitely; there needs to be constant rotation between t=
he=C2=A0abstract commodities in warehouses and the useful commodities in co=
mmerce.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still the system of=C2=A0permanent abstract co=
mmodities in exchange warehouses really is very convenient, so it tempts ag=
ricultural commodity traders too. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33301955.257406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDcvdHJhZGVycy1tb3ZlLWNvZmZlZS1hcm91bmQ=
tdG8taGlkZS1hZ2luZy1iZWFucy1mb3ItdGhlLWxhc3QtdGltZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTA4MjNfTU=
9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVyb=
T0yMzExMDgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB81a520a=
5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  a story about coffee</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stockpiles of premium coffee beans on the worl=
d=E2=80=99s biggest arabica exchange have plummeted to their lowest levels =
since 1999 as some sellers race to take advantage of a closing loophole one=
 last time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although dropping inventories held in global w=
arehouses monitored by Intercontinental Exchange Inc. would normally signal=
 soaring demand or a crimp in supplies, the more than 20% plunge seen in th=
e past month appears to be a strategic move ahead of a crucial Dec. 1 rule =
change.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For years, some sellers looking to avoid an =
=E2=80=9Cage penalty=E2=80=9D meant to discourage lengthy coffee storage ha=
ve pulled their older beans off the exchange and then resubmitted them for =
a new round of certification, thereby making the coffee appear fresh. That =
legal but misleading practice, which has led to roasters receiving older-th=
an-expected beans and obscured the true volume of coffee in the market, wil=
l be prohibited as of next month.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CJust plop coffee beans in the exchang=
e warehouse and leave them there forever=E2=80=9D obviously does not work, =
but =E2=80=9Cplop coffee beans in the warehouse, leave them there for a res=
pectable amount of time, take them out, walk them across the street, bring =
them back and plop them in again, repeatedly=E2=80=9D worked surprisingly w=
ell. In December it will stop working, though everyone gets to do it one mo=
re time first. In some ways=C2=A0the simpler=C2=A0solution would be to repl=
ace all the coffee beans with pebbles but I guess that would cause problems=
.</p>
