<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A reader who used to work at Bridgewater email=
ed=C2=A0that these points are more related than I thought:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You wrote=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cthe computer's ma=
in problem is keeping the 1,500 human employees busy so that they don=E2=80=
=99t interfere with its perfect rationality.=E2=80=9D You missed that the s=
tory right above that comment =E2=80=93 confronting Ray about his trading p=
erformance =E2=80=93 was a rather elegant attempt at doing just that. ...</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course Bridgewater is systematic =E2=80=93 =
not =E2=80=9Cquant=E2=80=9D in the Rennaissance=C2=A0Technologies sense, bu=
t systematic in the sense of =E2=80=9Ctrades are determined by computers ru=
nning complicated calculations across a thousand different rulesets.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">95% of the trades are made by the system. But =
also of course Ray could do whatever he wanted to, he owned the place (at t=
he time). The analysis Copeland heard about had nothing to do with Ray=E2=
=80=99s pure ability as a trader =E2=80=93 they were looking at <em>the tim=
es that Ray overruled the computer</em>.=C2=A0The point wasn=E2=80=99t =E2=
=80=9CRay is a bad investor,=E2=80=9D it was =E2=80=9CRay shouldn=E2=80=99t=
 overrule the computer.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The computer called Dalio=E2=80=99s underlings=
 into its little computer office and was like =E2=80=9Coh boy do I have a t=
ask for you, you have to tell that Dalio guy to stop messing with my trades=
.=E2=80=9D And they were like =E2=80=9Cthank you, computer,=C2=A0this is an=
 incredible opportunity for radical transparency and ideas meritocracy,=E2=
=80=9D I guess.</p>
